                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d610">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115 President Hoover/36: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-06T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 6, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 6—10:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>614. Department’s 211, September 3, 8 p.m.<note n="40" xml:id="d610fn40">Not
                        printed.</note> I assume that incident of the bombing of the <hi
                        rend="italic">President Hoover</hi> may be considered closed with the note
                    of the Minister for Foreign Affairs transmitted in my 598 of September 4, 3 p.m.
                    except for damages and I shall await <pb facs="0489" n="481" xml:id="pg_481"/>
                    Department’s instructions in regard to this. Damages should, I suppose, include
                    solatium for injury and loss of life.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department repeated to Peiping and Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
